I&#39;m sorry I didn&#39;t see this before writing my previous reply.

To check that the connection is established, I would write a test that 
issues a simple command against the database.

public void testConnectionEstablished() throws Exception {
     Connection connection = application.connectToDatabase();
     Statement statement = connection.createStatement(...some simple SQL 
statement...);
     statement.execute();
     statement.close();
     connection.close();
     // as long as no exception is thrown, the connection works
}

This test fails only if an exception is thrown, which would indicate the 
connection was not established correctly. Now I would write a method in 
your production code called &quot;connectToDatabase()&quot; to make the test pass.

To test whether the query is correct, just check the string.

public void testSelectSubmissionQuerySql() throws Exception {
     SubmissionQuery query = new SubmissionQuery();
     assertEquals(
         &quot;SELECT SUBMISSION_GUID FROM SUBMISSION WHERE SUBMISSION_GUID = 
143&quot;,
         query.getSql());
}

This test simply makes sure that if someone changes the query in 
SubmissionQuery, then they do it twice to verify that they really wanted 
to change it. This is much like entering a password twice when you 
register at a web site. Now I would create a new class SubmissionQuery 
that encapsulates the statement. (It looks like too much design now, but 
as your system grows, it will be very helpful.)

As for the result of the query, I would write this test:

public void testSelectSubmissionQueryOneRow() throws Exception {
     //... insert a row into the database with GUID 143
     SubmissionQuery query = new SubmissionQuery();
     Connection connection = application.connectToDatabase();
     List guids = query.execute(connection);
     assertEquals(Collections.singletonList(new Integer(143)), guids);
}

For the first comment, you need to put some sample data in the database 
so your test can find it. You can do this with some JDBC code or using a 
tool like DbUnit. Now you can implement SubmissionQuery.execute() with 
the code you wrote in your first posting, except this time, execute() 
accepts the Connection as a parameter. This way, you can test the 
connection separately. It will look like this:

class SubmissionQuery {
     public List execute(Connection connection) throws Exception {
         ResultSet resultSet = null;
         PreparedStatement selectStatement = null;
         List guids = new ArrayList();

         try {
             selectStatement =
                  connection.prepareStatement(getSql());
             resultSet = selectStatement.executeQuery();
             while(resultSet.next()) {
                 guids.add(resultSet.getInteger(&quot;SUBMISSION_GUID&quot;));
             }
         }
         finally {
             try {
                 if(resultSet != null) resultSet.close();
                 if(selectStatement != null) selectStatement.close();
             }
             catch (Exception nothingWeCanDo) {}
         }

         return guids;
     }
}

